===Preposition===
{{en-head|prep}}

# [[towards|Towards]]; in the [[direction]] of.
#: {{ux|en|The astronauts headed '''for''' the moon.}}
#: {{ux|en|Run '''for''' the hills!}}
#: {{ux|en|He was headed '''for''' the door when he remembered.}}
#* {{RQ:Bacon New Atlantis|page=1|passage=Wee ſailed from ''Peru'', (where wee had continued by the ſpace of one whole yeare,) '''for''' ''China'' and ''Iapan'', by the South Sea; [...]}}
# Directed at; [[intended]] to [[belong]] to.
#: {{ux|en|I have something '''for''' you.}}
# In order to help, benefit, gratify, honor etc. (someone or something).
#: {{ux|en|Everything I do, I do '''for''' you.}}
#: {{ux|en|We're having a birthday party '''for''' Janet.}}
#: {{ux|en|The mayor gave a speech '''for''' the charity gala.}}
#* {{quote-song|en|year=1976|author={{w|Michael McDonald (musician)|Michael McDonald}}|artist=w:The Doobie Brothers|title={{w|Takin' It to the Streets (song)|Takin' It to the Streets}}|passage=You, telling me the things you're gonna do '''for''' me.}}
# [[befitting|Befitting]] of someone’s beliefs, needs, wants, skills, or tastes; best suited to.
#: {{ux|en|If having to bag the groceries correctly is more than you can handle, then this isn't the job '''for''' you.}}
# To be used or treated in a stated way, or with a stated purpose.
#: {{ux|en|This is a new bell '''for''' my bicycle.}}
#: {{ux|en|The cake is '''for''' Tom and Helen's anniversary.}}
#: {{ux|en|This medicine is '''for''' your cough.}}
#: {{ux|en|These apples here are '''for''' eating. The rest are '''for''' throwing away.}}
#: {{ux|en|I'll buy something '''for''' killing cockroaches. We must find something to kill them all.}}
# [[support|Supporting]], in [[favour]] of.
#: {{ant|en|against}}
#: {{ux|en|All those '''for''' the motion, raise your hands.}}
#: {{ux|en|Who's '''for''' ice-cream?}}
#: {{ux|en|I'm '''for''' going by train}}
#: {{ux|en|Ten voted '''for''', and three against.|q=with implied object}}
#* {{RQ:Dickens Great Expectations|II|XI|180|"I'll go round presently, and pay our friend off." Rather alarmed by this summary action, I was '''for''' a little delay, and even hinted that our friend himself might be difficult to deal with.}}
# [[because of|Because of]].
#: {{ux|en|He wouldn't apologize; and just '''for''' that, she refused to help him.}}
#: {{ux|en|He looks better '''for''' having lost weight.|q=UK usage}}
#: {{ux|en|She was the worse '''for''' drink.}}
#: {{ux|en|I like her '''for''' lots of reasons.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-3|II|v|passage=with fiery eyes sparkling '''for''' very wrath}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1867|author=Frederick Metcalfe|title=The Oxonian in Iceland|page=202|passage="A summerly day for you," said my host; "You ought to be here in winter. It is impossible then to get out of the doors '''for''' the snow and wind. Ugh! dreadful weather!"}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1864|author=George Etell Sargent|title=The Story of a City Arab| page=313| passage=I could not see his hands, '''for''' the thick gloves he wore, and his face was partially concealed by a red woollen comforter; but his entire appearance and manners tallied with what I had seen of Yorkshire farmerhood.}}
# {{cap|in order to}} [[cure]], [[remove]] or [[counteract]].
#: {{ux|en|I need to spray my house '''for''' termites.}}
# So as to allow (something or someone) to take position.
#: {{ux|en|Make way '''for''' the president!}}
#: {{ux|en|Clear the shelves '''for''' our new Christmas stock!}}
# In anticipation of.
#: {{ux|en|Stand by '''for''' your cue.}}
#: {{ux|en|Prepare '''for''' battle.}}
# So as to identify or locate.
#: {{ux|en|They swept the area '''for''' enemy operatives.}}
#: {{ux|en|Police combed his flat '''for''' clues.}}
# Over (a period of time).
#: {{ux|en|I've lived here '''for''' three years.}}
#: {{ux|en|They fought '''for''' days over a silly pencil.}}
#: {{ux|en|The store is closed '''for''' the day.}}
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1717|author=w:Joseph Addison|title=Metamorphoses
|passage=To guide the sun's bright chariot '''for''' a day.}}
# Throughout or across (a distance in space).
#: {{ux|en|I can see '''for''' miles.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare King Lear|II|iv|passage='''For''' many miles about / There's scarce a bush.}}
# {{n-g|Used to introduce a subject of a [[to-infinitive]] clause.}}
#: {{ux|en|It seems unreasonable '''for''' our boss to withhold our wages.}}
#: {{ux|en|I don't think it's a good idea '''for''' you and me to meet.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''For''' you and me to meet is not a good idea because I'm not eager '''for''' it to be a success.}}
# On behalf of.
#: {{ux|en|I will stand in '''for''' him.}}
#: {{ux|en|I speak '''for''' the Prime Minister.}}
# In the role or capacity of; instead of; in place of.
#: {{ux|en|I used a hay bale '''for''' a bed.}}
#: {{ux|en|He's got a turnip '''for''' a brain.}}
# In exchange for; in correspondence or equivalence with.
#: {{ux|en|I got five hundred pounds '''for''' that old car!}}
#: {{ux|en|He matched me blow '''for''' blow.}}
#* {{RQ:King James Version|Exodus|21|23-24|passage=And if any mischief follow, then thou shalt give life '''for''' life, eye '''for''' eye, tooth '''for''' tooth, hand '''for''' hand, foot '''for''' foot.}}
# In order to [[obtain]] or [[acquire]].
#: {{ux|en|I am aiming '''for''' completion by the end of business Thursday.}}
#: {{ux|en|He's going '''for''' his doctorate.}}
#: {{ux|en|Do you want to go '''for''' coffee?}}
#: {{ux|en|People all over Greece looked to Delphi '''for''' answers.}}
#: {{ux|en|Can you go to the store '''for''' some eggs?}}
#: {{ux|en|I'm saving up '''for''' a car.}}
#: {{ux|en|Don't wait '''for''' an answer.}}
#: {{ux|en|What did he ask you '''for'''?}}
#* {{RQ:Denham Sophy|chapter=Prologue|passage=For we would have you know it, / The loſs will fall on us, not on the Poet: / For he writes not '''for''' money, nor '''for''' praiſe, / Nor to be call'd a Wit, nor to wear Bayes: {{...}}}}
# By the [[standard]]s of, usually with the implication that those standards are lower than one might otherwise expect; considering.
#: {{ux|en|Fair '''for''' its day.}}
#: {{ux|en|She's spry '''for''' an old lady.}}
#: {{usex|en|He's very mature, '''for''' a two-year-old.}}
# To [[be]], or [[as]] being.
#: {{ux|en|Don't take me '''for''' a fool.}}
#* '''17th century''' {{w|Abraham Cowley}}, ''[[s:Of Wit|Of Wit]]''
#*: We take a falling meteor '''for''' a star.
#* {{RQ:Locke Conduct|passage=if a man can be persuaded and fully assured of anything '''for''' a truth without having examined, what is there that he may not embrace for truth ?}}
#* '''c. 1690''', {{w|John Dryden}}, ''Translations'' (Preface)
#*: Most of our ingenious young men take up some cry'd-up English poet '''for''' their model.
#* {{quote-text|en|year=1712|author=w:Ambrose Philips|title=The Distrest Mother| passage=But let her go '''for''' an ungrateful woman.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1976|author=w:Louis L’Amour|title=The Rider of Lost Creek|publisher=Bantam Dell| isbn=978-0-553-89964-1| chapter=2| passage=They knew him '''for''' a stranger.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=13 Feb 82|volume=9|number=29|journal=Gay Community News|page=4|title=Unnatural|author=Wayne Dynes|text=I would advise anyone who does not share its politics — surely the great majority of gay men and lesbians — to shun NOLAG '''for''' the anachronistic zombie it is.}}
# {{lb|en|usually in the phrase '[[for all]]'}} [[despite|Despite]], [[in spite of]].
#: {{ux|en|'''For''' all his expensive education, he didn't seem very bright.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1898|author=w:H.G. Wells|title=w:The War of the Worlds|publisher=William Heinemann| location=London| page=113| passage="You must keep your head. There is still hope." "Hope!" "Yes; plentiful hope -- '''for''' all this destruction!"}}
#* '''1892''' August 6, "The Unbidden Guest", in {{w|Charles Dickens, Jr.}} (editor), ''{{w|All the Year Round}}'',<sup >[http://books.google.com/books?id=XNwRAAAAYAAJ]</sup> [http://books.google.com/books?id=XNwRAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA133&amp;dq=%22but+for%22 page 133],
#*: Mr. Joseph Blenkinshaw was perhaps not worth quite so much as was reported; but '''for''' all that he was a very wealthy man {{...}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1968|author=J. J. Scarisbrick|title=Henry VIII|page=240|passage='''For''' all his faults, there had been something lofty and great about him - as a judge, as a patron of education, as a builder, as an international figure.}}
# {{senseid|en|desired}} {{n-g|Indicating something desired or anticipated.}}
#: {{ux|en|O '''for''' the wings of a dove.}}
#: {{ux|en|Ah! '''for''' wings to soar&nbsp;…}}
#: {{ux|en|And now '''for''' a slap-up meal!}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|Prologue|text=O '''For''' a Muſe of Fire, that would aſcend / The brighteſt Heauen of Inuention :}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=March 27 1858|title=The Lay of the Brief|journal=Punch, Or, The London Charivari|page=129| passage=Oh! but to breathe the air / By their side under summer skies! To watch the blush on their cheeks, / The light in their liquid eyes. / Oh! but '''for''' one short hour, / To whisper a word of love; {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|in expressions such as '[[for a start]]'}} {{n-g|Introducing the first item(s) in a potential sequence .}}
#: {{ux|en|Go scuba diving? '''For''' one thing, I can't even swim.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''For''' another, we don't have any equipment.}}
# {{lb|en|with names|chiefly|US}} In [[honor]] of; after.
#: {{ux|en|He is named '''for''' his grandfather.}}
# {{lb|en|UK}} Due for or facing (a certain outcome or fate).
#: {{ux|en|He totally screwed up that project. Now he's surely '''for''' the sack.}}
# {{lb|en|chiefly|US}} [[out of|Out of]]; {{non-gloss|used to indicate a fraction, a ratio}}
#: {{ux|en|In term of base hits, Jones was three '''for''' four on the day}}
# {{lb|en|cricket}} {{non-gloss|Used as part of a score to indicate the number of wickets that have fallen.}}
#: {{ux|en|At close of play, England were 305 '''for''' 3.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} {{n-g|Indicating that in prevention of which, or through fear of which, anything is done.}}
#* {{RQ:Beaumont Fletcher Comedies and Tragedies|title=The Captain|act=III|scene=v|passage=We'll have a bib, '''for''' spoiling of thy doublet.}}
# {{lb|en|nonstandard}} [[So]] ([[that]]), [[in order to]]
#: {{uxi|en|He took the swing shift [[for]] he could get more overtime.}}
# {{n-g|Used in various other more-or-less idiomatic ways to construe individual verbs, indicating various semantic relationships such as target, purpose, result, etc.; see also the entries for individual phrasal verbs, e.g. [[ask for]], [[look for]], [[stand for]], etc.}}
#: {{ux|en|to account '''for''' one's whereabouts&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to care '''for''' a relative&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to settle '''for''' second best&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; to allow '''for''' mistakes}}

====Usage notes====
Some modern grammars classify the sense that introduces a subject of a [[to-infinitive]] clause as a {{l|en|subordinator|id=grammar}} rather than a preposition;<ref name="Pullum-2024">{{cite-book |en |year=2024 |last=Pullum |first=Geoffrey K. |authorlink=Geoffrey K. Pullum |title=The Truth About English Grammar |publisher=Polity Press |page=98 |isbn=978-1509560547}}</ref> most grammar books and dictionaries to date, being based on {{w|traditional grammar}}, classify it as a preposition rather than a [[subordinating conjunction]].<ref name="Pullum-2024"/>

